1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,680
Lecture 3, Divine Predestination and Foreknowledge

2
00:00:12,680 --> 00:00:24,680
In the last lecture, we looked at two forms of necessity, fate and karma.

3
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:30,480
Today, we'll look at notions of necessity that have arisen more recently from the Judeo-Christian

4
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:31,380
religious tradition.

5
00:00:31,940 --> 00:00:34,840
And once again, we'll look at two different forms of necessity.

6
00:00:35,340 --> 00:00:41,440
One idea is the idea of predestination, the idea that God has pre-planned everything that's

7
00:00:41,440 --> 00:00:42,080
going to happen.

8
00:00:42,660 --> 00:00:48,460
A very different idea that's related to questions about free will is the idea of divine omniscience,

9
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:52,640
that maybe God didn't plan everything that would happen, but he at least knows everything

10
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:53,300
that will happen.

11
00:00:53,300 --> 00:00:58,380
And we'll look at both of these issues and how they relate to the idea of free will,

12
00:00:58,500 --> 00:01:03,600
both divine predestination in relation to free will and divine omniscience in relation to

13
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:04,040
free will.

14
00:01:05,140 --> 00:01:11,480
The major religious movements in the Judeo-Christian tradition, Judaism, Christianity and Islam,

15
00:01:12,120 --> 00:01:17,260
at least some parts of them, some sects within those religions have embraced the idea of divine

16
00:01:17,260 --> 00:01:18,160
predestination.

17
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:23,300
And on that view, again, the idea is that God determined what would happen to each of

18
00:01:23,300 --> 00:01:23,600
us.

19
00:01:24,220 --> 00:01:30,400
And we find this in, not in the sort of broad traditions, that it isn't the case that the

20
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:36,580
entire religious tradition in Judaism or Christianity or Islam accepts predestination, but there are

21
00:01:36,580 --> 00:01:38,580
representative sects in each case.

22
00:01:38,580 --> 00:01:45,700
So, in Judaism, the early Jewish sect, the Essenes, accepted some form of predestination.

23
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:51,660
The Essenes were active around the time of Jesus, and it's thought that the Dead Sea Scrolls were

24
00:01:51,660 --> 00:01:53,620
written by members of the Essenes.

25
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:59,560
Most of what we know about the Essenes comes from the Bible and from the Jewish historian,

26
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:03,840
Josephus, who lived from about 37 to 101 CE.

27
00:02:04,540 --> 00:02:10,960
And Josephus says that the sect of the Essenes affirm that fate governs all things and that

28
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:13,960
nothing befalls men but what is according to its determination.

29
00:02:14,920 --> 00:02:20,780
So, the Essenes think that God has set everything out, that everything that happens to us has already

30
00:02:20,780 --> 00:02:22,400
been pre-planned by God.

31
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:30,020
In the Islamic tradition, a minor sect known as the Jabirites also maintained that God determines

32
00:02:30,020 --> 00:02:30,480
everything.

33
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:36,800
The issue of predestination in Islam is vexed, that many people in Islam are worried about

34
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:38,660
the possibility that everything is predestined.

35
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:43,320
The one sect that we know fully embrace predestination is the Jabirites.

36
00:02:44,100 --> 00:02:49,960
But the best-known version of predestination comes in the Christian tradition with Calvinism.

37
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:55,160
Most famously, the Calvinists accepted some form of predestination.

38
00:02:55,800 --> 00:03:02,500
John Calvin was a Protestant theologian who lived from 1509 to 1564, and he developed an

39
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:05,100
extremely influential form of Protestantism.

40
00:03:05,740 --> 00:03:11,760
And a critical part of this version of Protestantism was the doctrine of predestination.

41
00:03:12,300 --> 00:03:15,100
Calvin explains the view as follows.

42
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:21,060
He says, by predestination, we mean the eternal decree of God, by which he determined with

43
00:03:21,060 --> 00:03:24,500
himself whatever he wished to happen with regard to every man.

44
00:03:25,060 --> 00:03:30,580
All are not created on equal terms, but some are preordained to eternal life, others to eternal

45
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:31,200
damnation.

46
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:37,880
So, Calvin thinks that God pre-planned everything, including whether a particular individual would

47
00:03:37,880 --> 00:03:39,780
go to heaven or to hell.

48
00:03:40,380 --> 00:03:43,460
Now, you might wonder, why does Calvin adopt this view?

49
00:03:43,460 --> 00:03:44,940
And he's very confident about it.

50
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:52,100
Much of it has to do with the idea of original sin, that we're all born tainted with original

51
00:03:52,100 --> 00:03:52,520
sin.

52
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,300
Calvin thought that that was a crucial part of the Christian faith.

53
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:03,920
As a result, because we're all tainted by sin, none of us deserve salvation because we're

54
00:04:03,920 --> 00:04:04,940
all really wretched.

55
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:08,300
Salvation doesn't get earned by our activity.

56
00:04:08,300 --> 00:04:12,920
Rather, if we're going to be saved, if we're going to be saved and sent to heaven, it would

57
00:04:12,920 --> 00:04:16,380
only be because God elects us through his grace.

58
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:22,060
God decides he's going to give us a gift and let us have a pleasant afterlife as opposed

59
00:04:22,060 --> 00:04:23,120
to eternal damnation.

60
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:31,880
Another part of Calvin's reason for promoting predestination is biblical texts that can be

61
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:34,540
interpreted as supporting divine predestination.

62
00:04:34,540 --> 00:04:40,600
For example, we find a passage in the book of Romans that suggests that God loved Jacob

63
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:46,700
and hated Esau, but then the text continues, quote, though they were not yet born and had

64
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:48,960
done nothing, either good or bad.

65
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:53,920
So, God has decided that he doesn't like one and he likes the other, even before they've

66
00:04:53,920 --> 00:04:54,420
done anything.

67
00:04:55,140 --> 00:05:01,520
So, in the passage in Romans, this is connected with the idea that what matters for God's favors

68
00:05:01,520 --> 00:05:07,060
is not the deeds of the individual, but the election made by God, God's decision, yes,

69
00:05:07,120 --> 00:05:08,580
I'm going to save this individual.

70
00:05:10,940 --> 00:05:16,440
These religious movements that embrace predestination, you might wonder, well, what do they think about

71
00:05:16,440 --> 00:05:17,040
responsibility?

72
00:05:17,420 --> 00:05:20,060
What do they think about whether people deserve to be punished?

73
00:05:20,500 --> 00:05:22,100
That's a really interesting question.

74
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:24,020
Historically, how did they react to this?

75
00:05:24,140 --> 00:05:27,300
So, they think people are predestined for various activities.

76
00:05:27,780 --> 00:05:30,960
Do they think that they still deserve to be punished or rewarded?

77
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:37,060
Do they think their actions still merit some kind of responsibility attribution, some kind

78
00:05:37,060 --> 00:05:39,240
of sense of deserving activities?

79
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:45,460
And in all three cases, the Essenes, the Jabberites, and the Calvinists, the answer is yes.

80
00:05:45,500 --> 00:05:48,160
They think that people still do deserve to be punished.

81
00:05:48,460 --> 00:05:54,280
So, Josephus says that the Essenes allot to bad souls a dark and tempestuous den full of

82
00:05:54,280 --> 00:05:55,680
never-ceasing punishments.

83
00:05:56,260 --> 00:05:59,580
So, they think that people should be punished if they do bad things.

84
00:05:59,580 --> 00:06:04,800
And in the Dead Sea Scrolls, which, as I said, is presumed to have been written by Essenes,

85
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:10,920
we find a description of an initiation rite that includes the following curse on evildoers.

86
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:14,140
Be cursed because of all your guilty wickedness.

87
00:06:14,580 --> 00:06:17,740
May he deliver you up for torture at the hands of the vengeful Avengers.

88
00:06:18,400 --> 00:06:21,940
May he visit you with destruction by the hand of all the reekers of revenge.

89
00:06:22,460 --> 00:06:25,440
Be cursed without mercy because of the darkness of your deeds.

90
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:28,620
Be damned in the shadowy place of everlasting fire.

91
00:06:29,300 --> 00:06:33,920
So, these guys thought, yeah, when somebody does something bad, God should punish them

92
00:06:33,920 --> 00:06:38,200
and he should punish them severely, damning them to the shadowy place of everlasting fire.

93
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:45,340
When we turn to Islam, although there's variation, as I said, on whether predestination is true

94
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:51,080
in Islam, all parties, all Islamic sects agree that divine justice is guaranteed.

95
00:06:51,080 --> 00:06:56,120
That anything God does, any punishment he meets out, is appropriate.

96
00:06:56,380 --> 00:06:57,480
It's a just punishment.

97
00:06:58,540 --> 00:07:06,280
Now, we don't know what the Jabberites in Islam or the Essenes in Judaism said about the apparent conflict.

98
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:11,160
How did they think about this apparent conflict between responsibility and predestination?

99
00:07:11,540 --> 00:07:14,040
A lot of people think that there is this conflict between those.

100
00:07:14,040 --> 00:07:20,020
We don't know what the Essenes or the Jabberites thought about this, but Calvin faces the issue

101
00:07:20,020 --> 00:07:22,420
head on and discusses it at some length.

102
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:30,260
So, at one point in his works, he writes, none perish without deserving it, and the reprobates

103
00:07:30,260 --> 00:07:33,500
suffer nothing which is not accordant with the most perfect justice.

104
00:07:33,960 --> 00:07:37,140
So, he says, people deserve eternal damnation.

105
00:07:37,720 --> 00:07:40,360
He goes on to say something that I find kind of remarkable.

106
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:46,140
He says, and there is not the least occasion for our cavilling, cavilling, that's like minor

107
00:07:46,140 --> 00:07:46,800
complaints.

108
00:07:47,460 --> 00:07:55,260
So, questioning the propriety of being predestined to an eternal bout of suffering in hell, that's

109
00:07:55,260 --> 00:07:57,280
likened to whining about trivialities.

110
00:07:57,420 --> 00:08:02,620
That seems a little harsh to me, but Calvin thinks that people are just wretched, and so

111
00:08:02,620 --> 00:08:04,120
they deserve punishment.

112
00:08:04,620 --> 00:08:09,080
So, if a person is saved, it's only because God is granting them a gift.

113
00:08:09,080 --> 00:08:14,380
But his point is that that doesn't affect the idea that people deserve their punishment.

114
00:08:14,780 --> 00:08:16,840
Everybody deserves to go to hell, he thinks.

115
00:08:16,980 --> 00:08:19,140
It's just that God will save some of us.

116
00:08:20,180 --> 00:08:26,360
These kinds of views of predestination do seem to be troubling for the way we think about

117
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:27,000
responsibility.

118
00:08:27,380 --> 00:08:33,500
The idea that God has predetermined everything comes in some kind of intuitive conflict with

119
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:36,580
the idea of divine justice and moral responsibility.

120
00:08:36,580 --> 00:08:44,800
And the major Abrahamic religions, Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, have on the whole largely rejected

121
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:46,980
predestination views about God.

122
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:53,460
And part of the reason for this seems to come from the worry that it's unclear how it could

123
00:08:53,460 --> 00:08:59,580
be just for God to create someone who, by God's own plan, is condemned to hell.

124
00:08:59,580 --> 00:09:04,520
That's something that a lot of philosophers and theologians and ordinary people find really

125
00:09:04,520 --> 00:09:04,960
difficult.

126
00:09:05,660 --> 00:09:10,240
And there is a long history of debate about this, particularly in Christianity.

127
00:09:10,900 --> 00:09:13,640
And I want to give you some idea of how this played out.

128
00:09:13,740 --> 00:09:15,340
It's intrinsically interesting anyway.

129
00:09:15,480 --> 00:09:23,460
But in the fourth century, the theologian Pelagius, who lived from about 360 to 420, rejected the

130
00:09:23,460 --> 00:09:29,700
doctrine of original sin, which again is the view that according to which everybody is born with

131
00:09:29,700 --> 00:09:30,920
sin on their souls.

132
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:38,220
And in addition, Pelagius argued that our own free choices play a key role in whether we get

133
00:09:38,220 --> 00:09:38,820
to go to heaven.

134
00:09:39,020 --> 00:09:42,020
So how we choose determines whether we go to heaven.

135
00:09:43,400 --> 00:09:49,480
Pelagius's overall view was opposed by Augustine, who was one of the most important theologians in

136
00:09:49,480 --> 00:09:50,560
the history of Christianity.

137
00:09:51,080 --> 00:09:58,520
Augustine lived from 354 to 430, and he defended the doctrine of original sin, as well as the

138
00:09:58,520 --> 00:10:03,440
doctrine that we only get salvation through an act of God's grace, not through anything

139
00:10:03,440 --> 00:10:04,720
we can do ourselves.

140
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:08,720
This was the idea that Calvin was drawing on and building on.

141
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:15,180
Well before Calvin, Augustine maintained that what we all deserve is eternal damnation, and

142
00:10:15,180 --> 00:10:18,040
there's nothing we can do to make us deserve anything else.

143
00:10:18,040 --> 00:10:22,960
But God, through his grace, elects to provide salvation for some of us.

144
00:10:24,160 --> 00:10:25,400
Now, back to Pelagius.

145
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:31,700
According to some versions of the history, the catalyst for Pelagius's view, his view that

146
00:10:31,700 --> 00:10:36,960
we have free will, and it's an important part of what gets us into heaven, was Pelagius

147
00:10:36,960 --> 00:10:41,620
was dismayed at the lack of moral rectitude among practicing Christians.

148
00:10:42,420 --> 00:10:47,700
According to this story, he blamed the moral failings of Christians in the contemporary world

149
00:10:47,700 --> 00:10:54,200
partly on their belief that salvation depended entirely on God's grace, and not at all on

150
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:55,340
what we choose to do.

151
00:10:55,540 --> 00:11:02,120
His own proposal, that our own free choices determine our ultimate end, our own free choices

152
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:07,040
fix whether we go to heaven, that seemed much more likely to inspire good behavior.

153
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:14,680
At any rate, Pelagius was accused of heresy, largely for denying original sin, and indeed he was

154
00:11:14,680 --> 00:11:20,840
ultimately excommunicated, and the Catholic Church declared Pelagianism, the theology that

155
00:11:20,840 --> 00:11:22,640
he was promoting, to be a heresy.

156
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:30,700
But his defense of free will against predestination presaged further defenses from subsequent theologians.

157
00:11:30,700 --> 00:11:41,460
More than a millennium later, the Dutch theologian Jacob Arminius, who lived from 1560 to 1609, retained

158
00:11:41,460 --> 00:11:42,980
the idea of original sin.

159
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:45,580
That is a large part of what got Pelagius in trouble.

160
00:11:46,260 --> 00:11:53,340
But like Pelagius, Arminius rejected predestination and defended the view that people make free choices,

161
00:11:53,920 --> 00:11:58,000
and that God elects for salvation the ones who make the right choices.

162
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:03,720
So, you make your choices, and God will decide whether you go to heaven based on those choices.

163
00:12:04,540 --> 00:12:10,560
The school of thought that arose from Arminius' ideas was called Arminianism, and it was in direct

164
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:12,160
conflict with Calvinism.

165
00:12:13,380 --> 00:12:17,720
Arminianism kept most of the Protestant theology that Calvin was promoting.

166
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:21,640
It rejected this crucial tenet, though, of predestination.

167
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:29,780
It's worth noting, emphasizing, that Arminianism is consistent with the idea that God knows

168
00:12:29,780 --> 00:12:30,180
everything.

169
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:35,720
God can know how a person will exercise their free will, and God might accordingly know

170
00:12:35,720 --> 00:12:38,300
well ahead of time whether they'll go to hell.

171
00:12:38,940 --> 00:12:44,280
But what Arminius insisted on was that their choices will play a crucial part in where they

172
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:44,540
go.

173
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:49,300
So God will know whether they're going to go to hell, but what they choose will be an important

174
00:12:49,300 --> 00:12:50,960
part of what fixes that.

175
00:12:52,260 --> 00:12:57,280
So, Arminians maintain that God knows where each of his children would spend eternity, whether

176
00:12:57,280 --> 00:12:59,000
they would be in heaven or hell.

177
00:12:59,380 --> 00:13:05,020
But what choice the person makes, that's a crucial part of what determines where they'll

178
00:13:05,020 --> 00:13:06,220
end up spending eternity.

179
00:13:07,800 --> 00:13:14,040
There's a really interesting historical episode on this in 18th century American religious history,

180
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:19,720
an episode that looks at the difference between Arminian views and Calvinist views.

181
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:25,340
And this is because the Calvinist Puritans were probably the most important initial Christian

182
00:13:25,340 --> 00:13:26,860
presence in the New World.

183
00:13:27,960 --> 00:13:30,000
They were the dominant religion in the New World.

184
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:37,540
But a number of ministers began promoting Arminianism about predestination, the view that predestination

185
00:13:37,540 --> 00:13:40,060
was false, that God didn't predestine everybody.

186
00:13:40,060 --> 00:13:46,740
Rather, we make our own free choices, and those choices help determine whether we go to heaven

187
00:13:46,740 --> 00:13:47,180
or hell.

188
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:53,840
And interestingly, Arminianism came to overtake Calvinism as the dominant Protestant position

189
00:13:53,840 --> 00:13:56,460
about predestination in the New World.

190
00:13:57,080 --> 00:14:02,340
Now, I think that what's interesting about this is that the people, the people who were

191
00:14:02,340 --> 00:14:05,100
practicing their religion, were voting with their feet.

192
00:14:05,100 --> 00:14:11,440
The idea that our salvation depends on free will is a much more palatable option than the

193
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:13,660
predestinarianism that we got from Calvin.

194
00:14:14,220 --> 00:14:19,140
This is, of course, just one episode in religious history, but we know more generally that there

195
00:14:19,140 --> 00:14:23,600
was a great historical shift away from the idea of predestination.

196
00:14:25,360 --> 00:14:30,740
Many philosophers, then, and theologians were troubled by the apparent conflict between

197
00:14:30,740 --> 00:14:32,760
predestination and free will.

198
00:14:32,760 --> 00:14:38,640
But, perhaps more impressively, ordinary people seem to have been greatly moved by this as

199
00:14:38,640 --> 00:14:38,900
well.

200
00:14:39,420 --> 00:14:45,380
So much so that the predestinarian views did not get preserved nearly so well as the upstart

201
00:14:45,380 --> 00:14:48,020
rivals that emphasized the existence of free will.

202
00:14:48,140 --> 00:14:53,560
So far, we've been focusing on the strong claim that God preordained everything, that God

203
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:55,080
set everything up in advance.

204
00:14:55,080 --> 00:15:01,200
Even if we give up on that idea, there's still a threat to free will and responsibility in

205
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:03,360
contemporary Judeo-Christian beliefs.

206
00:15:03,920 --> 00:15:08,320
And that threat comes from the idea that God knows everything that we will do.

207
00:15:08,660 --> 00:15:10,860
That's the thesis of divine omniscience.

208
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:18,060
And divine omniscience is more widely adopted among the Judeo-Christian tradition, and it does

209
00:15:18,060 --> 00:15:20,820
seem to provide some kind of threat to free will.

210
00:15:20,820 --> 00:15:26,300
So, according to many Abrahamic religions, many of the Christian groups, Islamic groups,

211
00:15:26,440 --> 00:15:32,380
and Judaism itself, God doesn't pre-plan every event, but he does know everything.

212
00:15:32,740 --> 00:15:35,900
And that means that God knows all of our future actions.

213
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:38,180
So, God knows what I'll choose for dinner tonight.

214
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:40,540
He knows what band I'll like next.

215
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:42,480
He knows when I'll decide to go to the movies.

216
00:15:42,620 --> 00:15:44,920
He knows whether I'll decide to take a nap on the airplane.

217
00:15:45,420 --> 00:15:46,860
He knows all of that stuff.

218
00:15:46,860 --> 00:15:52,780
And that has been thought to be central to the religion, to the Abrahamic religions, because

219
00:15:52,780 --> 00:15:57,260
to say that God doesn't know everything is to impose a limitation on God.

220
00:15:57,340 --> 00:16:00,360
And God is supposed to be unlimited, and so God should know everything.

221
00:16:01,740 --> 00:16:06,640
Now, unlike the doctrine of predestination, the doctrine of omniscience is central to the

222
00:16:06,640 --> 00:16:12,520
Abrahamic religion, and yet it seems like there is some kind of tension between this view

223
00:16:12,520 --> 00:16:20,120
and free will, because even if God doesn't dictate my choices, the choices seem already

224
00:16:20,120 --> 00:16:21,000
to be mapped out.

225
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:26,240
They're pre-planned in that sense, that they're already, God already knows everything I'm going

226
00:16:26,240 --> 00:16:26,660
to do.

227
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,340
And that at least creates an initial worry.

228
00:16:29,860 --> 00:16:34,780
So, the initial worry is, if God knows everything I'm going to do, how can I really be free?

229
00:16:34,780 --> 00:16:41,080
And the theologian I mentioned a moment ago, Augustine, provided one important point.

230
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:46,560
He made one important point about this, that at least starts to allay the worries.

231
00:16:46,760 --> 00:16:52,240
So, he points out that even if God knows what we're going to decide, that doesn't mean that

232
00:16:52,240 --> 00:16:53,600
God forced the decision.

233
00:16:54,740 --> 00:16:58,900
God is predicting what we'll do, because he can see ahead to our free choices.

234
00:16:58,900 --> 00:17:05,320
He sees the choices we'll make, but Augustine says, we still make the choices for ourselves.

235
00:17:05,980 --> 00:17:08,520
And Augustine uses an analogy to make the point.

236
00:17:09,180 --> 00:17:15,080
He says, I can remember what I chose in the past, and there is no way for me to alter those

237
00:17:15,080 --> 00:17:15,540
decisions.

238
00:17:15,740 --> 00:17:21,200
So, I remember what I had for dinner last night, and I can remember deciding to take a job at

239
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:24,800
the University of Arizona, and I can remember deciding to have children.

240
00:17:24,900 --> 00:17:26,600
I can remember all of those decisions.

241
00:17:26,600 --> 00:17:30,060
There's no way I can change the fact that I made those decisions.

242
00:17:30,300 --> 00:17:33,880
I wouldn't want to change those decisions, except maybe about what I had for dinner.

243
00:17:34,340 --> 00:17:38,040
But that doesn't mean that those decisions in the past weren't free.

244
00:17:38,620 --> 00:17:40,360
Maybe those decisions were still free.

245
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:44,720
It's just that I can remember, I can know what the decisions were.

246
00:17:45,980 --> 00:17:49,280
Something similar can be said, then, about God's foreknowledge.

247
00:17:49,620 --> 00:17:51,560
He knows for a fact what we'll do.

248
00:17:51,560 --> 00:17:56,340
But this is no more a threat to our freedom, Augustine says, than is the memory of our past

249
00:17:56,340 --> 00:17:56,780
choices.

250
00:17:57,180 --> 00:18:00,560
It's a fact that I decided to move to the University of Arizona.

251
00:18:00,780 --> 00:18:03,540
But that doesn't mean that the choice wasn't free.

252
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:10,080
So, to take an example of someone else, a popular figure, a well-known figure, we all

253
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:14,320
know that Gerald Ford decided to pardon Richard Nixon.

254
00:18:14,320 --> 00:18:20,620
But the fact that we know about Ford's decision doesn't mean that Ford's decision wasn't free.

255
00:18:21,260 --> 00:18:28,140
So, just because God knows what my future decisions are, doesn't mean that my future decisions

256
00:18:28,140 --> 00:18:28,880
are unfree.

257
00:18:30,260 --> 00:18:37,180
At a minimum, it seems that divine omniscience isn't quite so troubling as divine predestination.

258
00:18:37,640 --> 00:18:43,340
For God, knowing what I will decide, is a far cry from God causing me to make the decision.

259
00:18:43,340 --> 00:18:48,880
Although this is somewhat comforting, many philosophers continue to think that there is

260
00:18:48,880 --> 00:18:49,740
a problem here.

261
00:18:50,540 --> 00:18:55,400
And the problem was brought out recently by the philosopher Nelson Pike, who's at the

262
00:18:55,400 --> 00:18:57,040
University of California, Irvine.

263
00:18:57,400 --> 00:19:02,860
And he's developed an influential argument that is aimed at showing that divine omniscience

264
00:19:02,860 --> 00:19:09,220
continues to be a problem, even if you acknowledge Augustine's point that God is not causing

265
00:19:09,220 --> 00:19:09,900
our decisions.

266
00:19:09,900 --> 00:19:15,620
So, let's start with the assumption that God is everlasting.

267
00:19:16,220 --> 00:19:19,680
That means God existed before the earth was created.

268
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:25,360
God will continue to exist after the earth is swallowed by the sun, that God continues to

269
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:26,900
exist throughout time.

270
00:19:27,880 --> 00:19:33,380
That means that since God is always omniscient, God always knows everything, then God knew before

271
00:19:33,380 --> 00:19:37,760
the earth was created that I would be giving these lectures on this particular day.

272
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:40,380
God also knew what I would be doing for a living.

273
00:19:40,560 --> 00:19:41,960
He knew whether I would believe in God.

274
00:19:42,040 --> 00:19:43,000
He knew all of that.

275
00:19:43,440 --> 00:19:48,860
For any action that we perform, for any decision we make, God knew before he created the earth

276
00:19:48,860 --> 00:19:49,600
that we would do it.

277
00:19:50,560 --> 00:19:56,660
We can call this divine foreknowledge because the idea is that God knew what I would do before

278
00:19:56,660 --> 00:19:57,400
I did it.

279
00:19:57,980 --> 00:20:00,240
Now, that is all just background.

280
00:20:00,600 --> 00:20:05,180
That's just clarifying what was already implicit in what we've discussed so far.

281
00:20:05,180 --> 00:20:08,420
But now we can get to the nub of Pike's argument.

282
00:20:09,180 --> 00:20:15,640
Pike says, if God knew before the earth existed that I would deliver this lecture today, then

283
00:20:15,640 --> 00:20:19,700
it was not in my power to do anything other than deliver this lecture today.

284
00:20:20,160 --> 00:20:22,920
I couldn't have refrained from presenting this lecture.

285
00:20:23,500 --> 00:20:28,800
For if it was in my power to do that, then it would have been in my power to make it the

286
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:32,000
case that some of what God thought he knew was false.

287
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,680
But that's impossible, Pike says.

288
00:20:35,360 --> 00:20:38,100
It would mean that I could make God not be omniscient.

289
00:20:38,520 --> 00:20:41,920
So I would have the power to make God have a false belief.

290
00:20:42,060 --> 00:20:44,640
And that, Pike says, is out of the question.

291
00:20:45,680 --> 00:20:50,620
Now, this is kind of a fancy argument because it depends on the idea that it couldn't even

292
00:20:50,620 --> 00:20:53,460
be possible that God has a false belief.

293
00:20:53,460 --> 00:20:59,200
But for our purposes, we can probably make do with something less formal and more intuitive.

294
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:05,220
And that is, if God knows what I'm going to do before I do it, then all of my behavior

295
00:21:05,220 --> 00:21:07,200
is fixed before I do it.

296
00:21:08,080 --> 00:21:12,800
Crucially, I don't have the power to do anything that departs from God's foreknowledge.

297
00:21:12,960 --> 00:21:15,100
I'm completely and utterly predictable.

298
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:18,240
At a minimum, this is really disorienting.

299
00:21:18,240 --> 00:21:22,700
It also suggests that my actions are not open in the way I might have thought.

300
00:21:23,400 --> 00:21:27,320
And this is really the core worry that philosophers continued to have.

301
00:21:27,800 --> 00:21:30,580
I think of my actions as being genuinely open.

302
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:33,480
I can raise my hand or not raise my hand.

303
00:21:34,120 --> 00:21:39,240
But if God already knows whether I'll raise my hand, then it seems that it is not really

304
00:21:39,240 --> 00:21:41,680
open to me to raise or not raise my hand.

305
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:45,300
I have to do whatever it is that God believes that I'll do.

306
00:21:45,300 --> 00:21:51,740
There is, though, a more powerful response to the problem of divine omniscience.

307
00:21:52,200 --> 00:21:56,820
And it comes from the idea that God's relation to time is very different from ours.

308
00:21:57,980 --> 00:22:04,220
The problem of divine omniscience is really a problem for free will because God knows what

309
00:22:04,220 --> 00:22:06,240
we'll do before we do it.

310
00:22:06,660 --> 00:22:12,840
That's why I tried to emphasize the idea of foreknowledge and that God exists in an

311
00:22:12,840 --> 00:22:13,880
everlasting sense.

312
00:22:13,880 --> 00:22:18,340
So if God knows what we'll do before we do it, then we arrive at these worries about

313
00:22:18,340 --> 00:22:22,480
whether I really have the power to act other than God believes I will.

314
00:22:23,480 --> 00:22:28,540
By contrast, to know about a person's choice as soon as they make the choice isn't a problem

315
00:22:28,540 --> 00:22:29,000
at all.

316
00:22:29,420 --> 00:22:32,060
So let's say I see you quickly swat a mosquito.

317
00:22:32,600 --> 00:22:35,180
I know about your choice roughly as it happens.

318
00:22:35,720 --> 00:22:38,240
But obviously, that's no barrier to free will.

319
00:22:38,320 --> 00:22:41,800
It's not like we say, well, I saw you make that decision so it wasn't free.

320
00:22:41,800 --> 00:22:45,700
Knowing your choice as you make it doesn't pose any problem at all.

321
00:22:46,700 --> 00:22:51,340
So knowledge of someone's present choices doesn't suggest that their choice isn't free.

322
00:22:52,280 --> 00:22:58,700
This kind of knowledge, the knowledge we have of a companion's present choices, some philosophers

323
00:22:58,700 --> 00:23:02,960
say that's the appropriate analogy for how God knows about our actions.

324
00:23:02,960 --> 00:23:08,580
And that's because God isn't everlasting as suggested in the foregoing argument.

325
00:23:08,820 --> 00:23:13,540
That is, it isn't the case that God existed before the earth, then created the earth, then

326
00:23:13,540 --> 00:23:14,580
watched what happened next.

327
00:23:14,940 --> 00:23:18,640
God isn't like a spectator watching as things occur in time.

328
00:23:19,360 --> 00:23:22,700
Rather, these philosophers suggested God is eternal.

329
00:23:23,240 --> 00:23:25,840
And that means literally outside of time.

330
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:31,140
And this was the idea that was promoted by the philosopher Boethius, who lived from 480

331
00:23:31,140 --> 00:23:32,040
to 524.

332
00:23:33,160 --> 00:23:39,560
The appeal to the notion of eternity does seem to provide an interesting solution to the

333
00:23:39,560 --> 00:23:41,720
problem of divine omniscience and free will.

334
00:23:42,320 --> 00:23:48,200
For in that case, we should think of God as perceiving our choices as they happen, not

335
00:23:48,200 --> 00:23:49,780
before he creates the earth.

336
00:23:50,200 --> 00:23:54,680
When God perceives our choices from God's perspective, it's always the present.

337
00:23:54,680 --> 00:23:57,180
So, for God, everything is simultaneous.

338
00:23:58,100 --> 00:24:03,800
So, just as it's no threat to your free will, if I see you choose vanilla right now, it's

339
00:24:03,800 --> 00:24:09,640
no threat to free will when God sees you choose vanilla in five years, because God's perception

340
00:24:09,640 --> 00:24:14,180
of that doesn't occur at some time prior to your choice, because that isn't how God is.

341
00:24:14,260 --> 00:24:17,540
God doesn't exist in this way that's stretched out across time.

342
00:24:17,900 --> 00:24:21,480
Everything for God occurs simultaneous, simultaneously.

343
00:24:21,480 --> 00:24:28,140
You might think that this is an unprincipled response to the objection, just trying to figure

344
00:24:28,140 --> 00:24:32,260
out some way to get out of the problem without any kind of principled basis.

345
00:24:33,020 --> 00:24:37,660
But in fact, Boethius thought that there was independent reason to believe that God should

346
00:24:37,660 --> 00:24:40,820
be thought of as eternal rather than everlasting.

347
00:24:40,820 --> 00:24:47,980
And the core idea is that the notion of being everlasting is just kind of beneath God.

348
00:24:48,300 --> 00:24:53,100
God is supposed to be perfectly simple, not somehow spread out across time.

349
00:24:53,860 --> 00:24:59,500
Rather, Boethius said, God possesses his existence, quote, completely and simultaneously.

350
00:25:00,220 --> 00:25:06,540
So, it can't be that God is somehow a composite made up of all of these different points on a

351
00:25:06,540 --> 00:25:06,960
timeline.

352
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:13,340
Another way that Boethius made the point was to say, if God existed in time, he would always

353
00:25:13,340 --> 00:25:18,120
be tied to the, quote, so-called present of the short and fleeting moment.

354
00:25:18,780 --> 00:25:24,420
And the general idea here is that being everlasting, existing in time, is inferior.

355
00:25:25,160 --> 00:25:27,780
God doesn't have to count the minutes until the next event.

356
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:31,820
He doesn't have to say, boy, look at his watch and say, geez, I can't wait until the movie

357
00:25:31,820 --> 00:25:32,140
starts.

358
00:25:32,180 --> 00:25:36,100
He doesn't have to do that, because everything appears simultaneously to God.

359
00:25:36,100 --> 00:25:40,800
His existence in time is very, very different from our existence in time.

360
00:25:42,160 --> 00:25:47,240
In addition, some philosophers have thought that God can't change, that if God is perfect,

361
00:25:47,340 --> 00:25:50,600
he can't change, because perfection is supposed to be singular.

362
00:25:51,240 --> 00:25:55,260
And existing throughout time would involve God in some kinds of changes.

363
00:25:55,760 --> 00:26:01,280
At a minimum, if God existed in time, God would change his relation to what counts as in the

364
00:26:01,280 --> 00:26:03,400
past as he passes through time.

365
00:26:03,400 --> 00:26:09,080
Although the eternity response seems to solve the problem, it's actually quite an ingenious

366
00:26:09,080 --> 00:26:09,560
solution.

367
00:26:10,040 --> 00:26:12,380
A number of philosophers have resisted this solution.

368
00:26:12,980 --> 00:26:19,240
And one reason is because it seems to conflict with biblical texts that suggest that God is

369
00:26:19,240 --> 00:26:21,500
really everlasting rather than eternal.

370
00:26:22,320 --> 00:26:28,680
So most scriptural accounts of God portray God as interacting in the world in ways that seem

371
00:26:28,680 --> 00:26:31,160
to conflict with the eternity interpretation.

372
00:26:31,360 --> 00:26:36,940
Just to take one familiar example, God notices that people are behaving in bad ways.

373
00:26:37,240 --> 00:26:38,740
He plans to produce a flood.

374
00:26:38,960 --> 00:26:40,400
He tells Noah to build an ark.

375
00:26:40,740 --> 00:26:43,860
After Noah builds the ark, God then produces the flood that he promised.

376
00:26:44,380 --> 00:26:48,300
It sure looks like God exists in time if we're to believe this story.

377
00:26:48,300 --> 00:26:55,380
Some theologians maintain that there's a mistake here in suggesting that this shows that God

378
00:26:55,380 --> 00:27:01,340
exists in time, because what's really going on is God's actions are in time for us.

379
00:27:01,520 --> 00:27:02,940
That's how we understand them.

380
00:27:03,100 --> 00:27:05,320
But that doesn't mean that they're in time for God.

381
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:11,480
So while in Noah's case there was a particular day on which Noah heard from God, it needn't

382
00:27:11,480 --> 00:27:16,200
have been the case that from God's perspective this happened at a particular moment in time

383
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:19,540
that he existed before and after which he still existed.

384
00:27:21,240 --> 00:27:26,940
According to some contemporary philosophers, though, the view of God as eternal seems particularly

385
00:27:26,940 --> 00:27:29,960
clearly in conflict with Christian views.

386
00:27:30,520 --> 00:27:36,740
Because in Christianity, God sends his son to redeem mankind after the fall, after they

387
00:27:36,740 --> 00:27:38,560
have come into sin.

388
00:27:38,560 --> 00:27:43,440
In this case, it seems like God is responding to what happened in the world.

389
00:27:43,840 --> 00:27:49,300
Indeed, it seems like what's going on is God is responding to the free choices of people.

390
00:27:50,760 --> 00:27:57,360
And the Yale philosopher Nicholas Wolterstorff articulates this view as follows.

391
00:27:57,480 --> 00:28:01,700
He said, God was not content to leave man in the mire of his misery.

392
00:28:02,300 --> 00:28:07,040
Aware of what is going on, he has resolved, in response to man's sin and its resultant evils,

393
00:28:07,040 --> 00:28:08,380
to bring about renewal.

394
00:28:08,380 --> 00:28:13,660
He has indeed already been acting in accord with that resolve centrally and decisively

395
00:28:13,660 --> 00:28:16,780
in the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus Christ.

396
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:22,680
So Wolterstorff certainly thinks that this doesn't fit with standard Christian theology,

397
00:28:22,820 --> 00:28:24,460
the idea of God being eternal.

398
00:28:25,460 --> 00:28:30,460
But this isn't the end of the story because it might be that our own limited understanding

399
00:28:30,460 --> 00:28:34,440
that forces us into these kinds of interpretations.

400
00:28:34,840 --> 00:28:40,940
Maybe God is standing outside of time, but we perceive his actions as being in time simply

401
00:28:40,940 --> 00:28:44,480
because they're happening to us, beings who are in time.

402
00:28:44,980 --> 00:28:49,780
Or, depending on one's views about the Bible, maybe the authors of the Bible were presenting

403
00:28:49,780 --> 00:28:52,600
the events through their own limited understanding of the truth.

404
00:28:52,600 --> 00:28:58,520
The Bible might present things in ways that we can easily grasp, even though their true

405
00:28:58,520 --> 00:29:01,220
nature might be very different from our understanding.

406
00:29:02,280 --> 00:29:09,060
But this defense of the eternity solution leads us directly into another main reason some philosophers

407
00:29:09,060 --> 00:29:11,780
are dissatisfied with the eternity solution.

408
00:29:12,360 --> 00:29:15,820
And that is that it's not clear what eternity is.

409
00:29:16,360 --> 00:29:20,040
This notion of eternity is very difficult for us to comprehend.

410
00:29:20,040 --> 00:29:25,760
And so the worry is that what Boethius has done is he's taken this difficult problem of

411
00:29:25,760 --> 00:29:28,920
divine omniscience, and he's just thrown a mystery out of it.

412
00:29:28,960 --> 00:29:30,560
He's just said, well, here's the solution.

413
00:29:30,840 --> 00:29:34,960
Something you don't understand, eternity, explains why God can do this.

414
00:29:35,860 --> 00:29:40,640
Now, a number of philosophers and theologians find this very discouraging, that trying to

415
00:29:40,640 --> 00:29:47,080
solve a problem by invoking a mystery doesn't seem like it gets us very far advanced in the

416
00:29:47,080 --> 00:29:47,800
dialectic.

417
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:53,580
But you may think that since the notion of God is already mysterious in important ways,

418
00:29:53,840 --> 00:29:59,000
if you believe in God, you might not find it all that far-fetched to add to the mystery

419
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:03,100
that, in addition to the other things that are mysterious about God, God is eternal.

420
00:30:04,500 --> 00:30:10,960
Now, if God is eternal in the way suggested by Boethius, this does seem to make the problem

421
00:30:10,960 --> 00:30:14,160
of divine omniscience much less of a threat to our free will.

422
00:30:14,160 --> 00:30:18,940
This is a case where a philosopher really came up with a pretty interesting idea about

423
00:30:18,940 --> 00:30:20,200
how to solve the problem.

424
00:30:21,340 --> 00:30:29,040
So, we've seen that in the kinds of views of religious determinism that we've had, or

425
00:30:29,040 --> 00:30:34,200
religious necessity that we've looked at, divine predestination and divine omniscience

426
00:30:34,200 --> 00:30:37,040
provide two different kinds of threats to free will.

427
00:30:37,040 --> 00:30:43,720
But most philosophers, most theologians, most believers in religion reject the divine

428
00:30:43,720 --> 00:30:44,860
predestination view.

429
00:30:44,860 --> 00:30:50,200
And the divine omniscience view seems like it doesn't force us into a full-scale rejection

430
00:30:50,200 --> 00:30:50,900
of free will.

431
00:30:51,040 --> 00:30:52,720
There are moves that can be made.

432
00:30:53,700 --> 00:30:57,880
In the next lecture, though, we'll look at views that suggest that every single action

433
00:30:57,880 --> 00:31:03,920
we perform is determined globally, and it has nothing to do with God knowing things.

434
00:31:03,980 --> 00:31:07,120
It's just a fact about the way the world is constructed.

435
00:31:07,120 --> 00:31:07,160
Thank you.

